The objective of this prototype test plan is to make sure we address the most critical components of our glue dispensing jig for novel polymer mircochannel heat exchangers. To do this, the top 5 at-risk components from our Design Failure Mode Analysis (DFMEA) have been selected for further analysis. The components in order of highest to lowest risk are as follows: our ability to assemble a full heat exchanger within a working day, the adhesives' life cycle, the MPHX jig's linearity, issues with adhesive bonding the jigs together, the lamina ridges interfering with the jig stacking, and the feed bearings being misaligned. These components can be further reduced to 3 main tests, adhesive testing, jig (both lamina and MPHX) testing, and a complete run through of the roller system. The following test plan will cover how we plan on testing the highest failure modes to make sure the glue dispensing jig runs smoothly.


The two of the top rated risks from our DMFEA are related to the jig design. The jig test will be done in three parts: checking the MPHX jig's linearity, making sure the MPHX jig doesn't receive glue from the roller applicator in unintended spots resulting in accidental adhesion.

